2.7/ definitions: \
\
Agent : anything that perceives its environment through sensors and acts upon it through actuators.\
Agent Function: The abstract mathematical mapping from the complete perception history to an action: f(history) -> action. It is \'93ideal specification\'94 of what the agent should do. It exists in paper, not in code.\
Agent Program: The actual code implementation of the agent function running on a real machine. It only receives the current perception and uses internal state to handle history.\
Rationality: An agent is rational if it always picks the action that maximizes its expected performance measure, given what it has perceived so far and what it knows - doing the best it can, not the best that\'92s possible overall.\
Autonomy: the degree to which an agent relies on its own experience and learning rather than built-in knowledge from the designer. Fully autonomous agents learn and adapt.\
\
The agent types in order of sophistication:\
\
- Reflex agent : the simplest ; looks at current perception only and fires a condition-action rule. e.g. smoke detector: smoke -> alarm\
- Model-based agent; maintains an internal model of the world to handle partial observability. Tracks how the world evolves even when it can\'92t directly observe it.\
- Goal-based agent; has a world model, and also explicit goals to reach. It can reason about sequences of actions to reach the goal. Changing goal changes behavior.\
- Utility-based agent: goes beyond goals by having a utility function that scores how desirable each state is. It can handle tradeoffs. e.g. reaching a goal faster vs safer.\
-Learning agent: has four components: learning element, performance element, a critic, and a problem generator. It can improve performance, select actions, evaluate the performance against standards and suggest exploratory actions. \
