2.16/ In a stochastic world: action -> Probability distribution over outcomes. This fundamentally changes agent design:\
\
- You can\'92t trust your actions always work\
- You can\'92t trust your sensors always work\
- You can\'92t assume world stays the same as you left it.\
\
Problem 1; Murphy\'92s law. The suck action has 3 possible outcomes instead of 1: works correctly, fails to clean, deposits dirt.\
A naive reflex agent breaks; A rational agent must verify and retry. So the agent needs to check the square once more after sucking: This requires internal state. \
Problem 2; Noisy sensor. Clean is perceived as dirty and vice versa. The agent needs to use probabilistic reasoning. This means either taking multiple readings or using Bayesian updating.\
Problem 3; Dynamic environment; The agent needs to keep patrolling forever. \
